When you define a new custom field type and want to be able to search over it you currently need to define a new customfield-searcher as well. Sometimes you want to be able to use an existing searcher. Currently you achieve this by defining a new customfield-searcher that is the same as an existing searcher but with a different set of valid-customfields. It would be nice if you could do this configuration from within the customfield itself rather than having to define this dummy customfield-searcher.

http://docs.atlassian.com/jira/3.13.3/com/atlassian/jira/issue/search/searchers/IssueSearcher.html goes bold and never goes unbold.
The problem is that "could" should be "strong" in this Javadoc in IssueSearcher.java

{noformat}
    /**
     * Initialises the searcher with a given field.
     * @param field the field object. This <strong>may</could> be null. (So you can have searchers on non-fields)
     */
    void init(SearchableField field);
{noformat}

When the value of multi-select custom field is retrieved by using Python XML-RPC, only the first value of the selection is displayed. For example,

Source:
{noformat}
import xmlrpclib

s = xmlrpclib.ServerProxy('http://localhost:8080/rpc/xmlrpc')
auth = s.jira1.login('admin', 'admin')

print s.jira1.getIssue(auth, 'PA-1')
{noformat}

Result:
{noformat}
{'status': '1', 'project': 'PA', 'updated': '2009-04-30 21:41:39.64', 'votes': '0', 'components': [], 'reporter': 'admin', 'customFieldValues': [{'values': 'A', 'customfieldId': 'customfield_10000'}], 'created': '2009-04-30 21:41:39.64', 'fixVersions': [], 'summary': 'test', 'priority': '3', 'assignee': 'admin', 'key': 'PA-1', 'affectsVersions': [], 'type': '1', 'id': '10000'}
{noformat}

Even though the multi-select custom field value displayed in the view issue screen is A, B, C. It's just showing the 'A' value.
